comments.body: Bill, the wild pigs/wild hogs/feral hogs that we have in Texas, they do not qualify as Sus scrofa ssp. domesticus as they are not simply farm pigs that have escaped and reproduced in the wild.  Nor do farm pigs introduced into the wild eventually re-evolve into Eurasian Wild Boars, no more than would a pack of wild Beagles re-evolve into Grey Wolves.  Domesticated pigs have been breeding ferally on this continent for several hundred years, that much is true.  But a hundred years or so ago (according to TPWD), the Eurasian Wild Boar was brought over and either intentionally or accidentally introduced into the wild, where they bred extensively with the feral pig population.  Today the hogs that roam the countryside are neither Eurasian Wild Boars nor Feral Domesticated Pigs; there are none of those remaining, at least not in any functional numbers, they have bred themselves out.  We have the interbred descendants of them, rather stabilized in morphology, readily discerned from both parents.  I can see how referring to them as "Wild Boar" trips up most fellow Texans, as we tend to refer to them locally as "pigs" or "hogs" and for whatever reason associate the term "boar" with the larger Eurasian beasts.  But I think we can agree that breeding one type of Sus scrofa with another type of Sus scrofa gets you a big population of Sus scrofa, gifted with high reproduction rates and absent the natural predators of Grey Wolves and Tigers, has spread like wildfire throughout Texas.

Recent information seems to suggest that Boars and Domestic pigs are much more closely related than we imagined. 

http://www.iflscience.com/plants-and-animals/domestic-pigs-continued-mate-wild-boars/

https://phys.org/news/2015-09-modern-pigs-wild-boar-genes.html

Here was my own observation of what I called a Wild Boar. 

https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/8237718

So there may actually be both Wild Boars and Feral Pigs which are nearly the same animal. I think we may be seeing pigs that look like domestics that are only recent 'wild' pigs. Those that are in the wild longer and are breeding with Boars (let's assume the Boar population has grown quickly as well) look more Boar like. Still, like I said, this is splitting hairs and remains an academic exercise, don't you think?
There are a few natural predators out there preying on wild pigs - including in our area and yours, Cougars, Bobcats and probably Coyotes. Problem is our rancher neighbors, farmers and hunters willingly kill these larger predators every chance they get which results in lessening pressure on wild living P I G Hogs or whatever we rather call them. Since the sources above suggest a very close relationship, the resulting animals similar appearance isn't surprising.
